169. Majority Element

----ELEMENT THAT present in array half of the time or more than half 

1) sort array 
2) return and element at middle index of array 


The Boyer-Moore Majority Voting Algorithm is a clever method to find the majority element 
(an element that appears more than âŒŠn/2âŒ‹ times) in an array using linear time and constant space.

ğŸ”‘ Key Idea
- If an element occurs more than half the time in the array, it will "outvote" all other elements combined.
- The algorithm maintains:
- Candidate: a potential majority element.
- Count: a counter tracking support for the candidate.

âš™ï¸ Algorithm Steps
- Initialization
- Set candidate = None and count = 0.
- First Pass (Find Candidate)
- Traverse the array:
- If count == 0, set candidate = current element and count = 1.
- If current element == candidate, increment count.
- Else, decrement count.
- ğŸ‘‰ At the end of this pass, candidate will be the potential majority element.
- Second Pass (Verification)
- Count how many times candidate actually appears in the array.
- If occurrences > âŒŠn/2âŒ‹, return candidate; otherwise, return "no majority element".

ğŸ“Š Example
Array: [1, 1, 2, 1, 3, 1, 1]
- Step 1: Candidate becomes 1, count fluctuates but stabilizes.
- Step 2: Verify â†’ 1 appears 5 times out of 7 (> 7/2).
âœ… Majority element = 1
Array: [1, 2, 3]
- Candidate may be 3, but verification shows no element > 1.5 times.
âŒ No majority element.

-------------------------------------------------------

class Solution {
    public int majorityElement(int[] nums) {
        Arrays.sort(nums);
        return nums[nums.length/2];        
    }
}

---------------------------------------------

class Solution {
    public int majorityElement(int[] nums) {
    /*    Arrays.sort(nums);
        return nums[nums.length/2];   */
         int count=0;
         int candidates=0;
        for(int x:nums){
            if(count==0){
                candidates=x;
            }
            count+=(x==candidates)?1:-1;}       return candidates;
    }}
